natural problem: If $f(x) = 2x + 3$ and $g(x) = 3x - 2$ find $\frac{f(g(f(2)))}{g(f(g(2)))}$. Express your answer in the form $\frac{a}{b}$.

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x :: real and f g :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. f x = 2 * x + 3"
and h1 : "\<forall> x. g x = 3 * x - 2"
shows  "f (g (f 2)) / g (f (g 2)) = 41 / 31"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 If $f(x) = 2x + 3$ and $g(x) = 3x - 2$ find $\frac{f(g(f(2)))}{g(f(g(2)))}$. Express your answer in the form $\frac{a}{b}$. The final Answer is \frac{41}{31}
 ### Proof
 We have $f(2) = 2(2) + 3 = 7$ and $g(2) = 3(2) - 2 = 4$, so \[\frac{f(g(f(2)))}{g(f(g(2)))} = \frac{f(g(7))}{g(f(4))}.\] We then have $g(7) = 3(7) - 2 = 19$ and $f(4) = 2(4) + 3 = 11$, so we have \[\frac{f(g(7))}{g(f(4))} = \frac{f(19)}{g(11)} = \frac{2(19) + 3}{3(11) - 2} = \boxed{\frac{41}{31}}.\]
 *)
